From c0ffee0000000000000000000000000000010aa Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Jiaxing Hu <huhuvmb88@outlook.com>
Date: Tue, 8 Jul 2026 17:30:00 +1200
Subject: [PATCH] arm64: dts: rk3576-rock-4d: keep the NPU rail (vdd_npu_s0) on

The ROCK 4D board DTS marks the NPU supply vdd_npu_s0 (dcdc-reg2 on the
RK806) only `regulator-boot-on`, not `regulator-always-on`. The vendor rknpu
driver enables the rail on the first NPU power-on and disables it again on
power-off, so once probe balances its enable/disable the regulator core's
boot-time cleanup (regulator_init_complete, ~30 s after boot) sees no active
consumer and disables the rail: "vdd_npu_s0: disabling".

The genpd NPU power domain, however, still reports "on" (the PMU status bit is
decoupled from the PMIC rail). So the *next* NPU use hits the early-return in
rockchip_pd_power() -- `if (rockchip_pmu_domain_is_on(pd) == power_on) return 0`
-- and neither re-enables the domain clocks nor re-runs the power-on setup,
while the rail itself is dead. The driver then reads an NPU MMU bank register
on an unpowered core; the MMIO read never completes and wedges the CPU (RCU
stall, broadcast timer dead). Result: the first NPU inference after boot works
(cold rail still up) but the second hangs the board.

The vendor BSP / the buildroot linux-next kernel that runs this stack at
9.3 tok/s carry `regulator-always-on` on vdd_npu_s0; stock mainline does not.
Add it so the NPU rail stays up and every NPU power-on lands on a live core.
This is the actual fix for the "second inference wedges the board" symptom
(pmdomain patches 0001/0002/0006/0009 make the *cold* power-on correct; this
is what makes re-use correct).

Signed-off-by: Jiaxing Hu <huhuvmb88@outlook.com>
---
 arch/arm64/boot/dts/rockchip/rk3576-rock-4d.dts | 1 +
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+)

diff --git a/arch/arm64/boot/dts/rockchip/rk3576-rock-4d.dts b/arch/arm64/boot/dts/rockchip/rk3576-rock-4d.dts
index aaaaaaaaaaaaa..bbbbbbbbbbbbb 100644
--- a/arch/arm64/boot/dts/rockchip/rk3576-rock-4d.dts
+++ b/arch/arm64/boot/dts/rockchip/rk3576-rock-4d.dts
@@ -438,6 +438,7 @@
 			};

 			vdd_npu_s0: dcdc-reg2 {
+				regulator-always-on;
 				regulator-boot-on;
 				regulator-enable-ramp-delay = <400>;
 				regulator-min-microvolt = <550000>;
